article.description:
Michael Olowokandi scored 25 points and the
Los Angeles Clippers beat the Memphis Grizzlies 92-84 Tuesday night to snap a three-game losing streak.
article.headline: Clippers on verge of 9th straight losing season
article.linkText: Clippers halt three-game skid with win over Grizzlies
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Clippers inched closer to the only goal that's still achievable in yet another losing season: 40 victories.
Gasol

Michael Olowokandi scored 25 points and the Clippers beat the Memphis Grizzlies 92-84 Tuesday night to snap a three-game losing streak. Their 39-42 mark represents an improvement of eight wins from last year, and they completed their home schedule with a 25-16 record. The close the season at Golden State. "I haven't had 40 wins since I've been here," said Eric Piatkowski, now in his eighth season. "It would be a nice thing to look at, and next year it would be something we could grow upon. Hopefully, we get maybe 50 wins next season, which I don't think is too unrealistic at all." Pau Gasol, a heavy favorite to win NBA rookie of the year honors, led five Grizzlies in double figures with 19 points and 11 rebounds. Fellow rookie Shane Battier added 17 points. Memphis needs a win Wednesday in its season finale at Seattle for its franchise-record 24th victory. "Whether we win 23 or 24, it was still an excellent season for these guys," Grizzlies coach Sidney Lowe said. "I'm more concerned about the future of the franchise, getting a look at these young guys because we have decisions to make." The Clippers led by 13 points in the fourth quarter on a 3-pointer by Quentin Richardson, who finished with 13 points. But Memphis ran off eight straight points to get to 82-77 with 5:03 remaining. The Grizzlies got no closer, and Richardson's second 3-pointer of the quarter restored the Clippers' lead to 10 points. "It was good that everyone came out and just played loose and had fun," said Corey Maggette, who had 13 points. "We were struggling, so we got back on track with a win. Hopefully we can play as hard as we did tonight and get us a win tomorrow." Los Angeles' Elton Brand had eight points and 10 rebounds, falling one basket short of his 55th double-double of the season, which would have broken Swen Nater's single-season club record set in 1980-81. Brand's basket with 1:45 failed to beat the shot clock, then he missed a 3-footer his next trip down the floor. "I didn't realize what was going on until it was a little late," he said. "It would've been nice to get it at home. I've still got a chance to break the record tomorrow. If not, tying the record will still go in the record books." Memphis led by eight points in the first half, when the Clippers shot 50 percent and took a 48-41 lead into the break. Two consecutive 3-pointers by Piatkowski, another by Maggette and two baskets by Olowokandi gave Los Angeles a 15-point lead in the third quarter, its largest of the game. Game notes
Brand is 21 minutes from becoming the first Clipper in nine seasons to log 3,000 minutes. He has 2,979 so far. Mark Jackson played 3,117 minutes in 1992-93. ... Clippers G Jeff McInnis missed the game with a left thigh bruise he sustained Saturday against Minnesota. He is questionable for the season finale. ... Memphis G Brevin Knight missed his 14th consecutive game because of plantar fasciitis in his left foot. The Grizzlies have lost 288 man-games to injury, the most in team history. ... Los Angeles won the season series, 3-1. ... Brand addressed the crowd of 20,264 -- the team's record 25th sellout -- before tipoff and thanked them for their support. "We're going to work hard in the offseason so we can make it to the playoffs because you guys deserve it," he said.
